Load Libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(sf)
library(tmap)
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)

Read Data

# Read NC Zip Code COVID data
nc.zip.covid <- st_read("../Data/NC_ZIP_COVID.shp", 
                        quiet = TRUE)

Descriptive Statistics

# Create summary information holder
# for Deaths per 1000 residents information
summary.table <- tibble(Measure = c("Observations",
                                    "Minimum",
                                    "Maximum",
                                    "Mean",
                                    "Median",
                                    "Standard Deviation"),
                        `Cumulative Cases` = c(sum(!is.na(nc.zip.covid$CASES)),
                                       min(nc.zip.covid$CASES, na.rm = TRUE),
                                       max(nc.zip.covid$CASES, na.rm = TRUE),
                                       mean(nc.zip.covid$CASES, na.rm = TRUE),
                                       median(nc.zip.covid$CASES, na.rm = TRUE),
                                       sd(nc.zip.covid$CASES, na.rm = TRUE)
                                       ),
                        `Case Rate` = c(sum(!is.na(nc.zip.covid$CASERATE)),
                                      min(nc.zip.covid$CASERATE, na.rm = TRUE),
                                      max(nc.zip.covid$CASERATE, na.rm = TRUE),
                                      mean(nc.zip.covid$CASERATE, na.rm = TRUE),
                                      median(nc.zip.covid$CASERATE, na.rm = TRUE),
                                      sd(nc.zip.covid$CASERATE, na.rm = TRUE)
                                      )
                        )

## Print nice version of the table
kable(summary.table, 
      digits = 1,
      format.args = list(big.mark = ",",
                         scientific = FALSE,
                         drop0trailing = TRUE),
      caption = "Summary of North Carolina COVID-19 Cumulative Cases and Case Rates (per 1,000 residents) by Zip Code") %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", 
                                      "hover", 
                                      "condensed", 
                                      "responsive"), 
                full_width = F)

## plot histogram

  ggtitle("Histogram of COVID-19 Case Rates") +
  theme_minimal()

Question 1. Write one sentence that uses information from the table above to describe the central tendency and dispersion of Cumulative COVID-19 Case Rates (per 1,000 people) by Zip Code. (1 sentence, using at least one measure of central tendency and one measure of dispersion)

One measure of central tendency is the mean, the mean (or in other words average) of cumulative COVID-19 Case Rates is 257.9, additionally, a measure of dispersion is the standard deviation (or in other words how dispersed the data is in relation to the mean) which is fairly high at 342.3.

Question 2. What is the difference between Histogram 1 and Histogram 2? Which one of these is more effective and why? (2-3 sentences)

The difference between Histogram 1 and Histogram 2 is that the bin width in the first is set to .5 while the bin width in the second is set to 2. In this case, Histogram 2 is more effective at accurately displaying the data because when the bin width is too small (as it is in Histogram 1) it can distort bar height and misrepresent the data which we can see when comparing the first bin (at 0) and the bins that peak in count (around 10-20). When looking at the bins that peak in count in the first histogram it appears that they only have about 10 more counts then the first bin but when looking at the second histogram it is apparent that there is actually a much larger difference between the two at around 60 counts.

Question 3. What are the differences between the data distributions found in Histogram 2 and Histogram 3? (2-3 sentences)

Histogram 2 shows the distribution of cumulative COVID-19 cases per 1,000 People while Histogram 3 just shows cumulative COVID-19 cases overall. While both graphs are skewed right, Histogram 3 is much more drastically skewed. Additionally the y-axis of Histogram 3 has a much larger range from around 0 - 150 while Histogram 2 has a smaller range in count from around 0 - 80.

Question 4. Why is Choropleth Map 2 more appropriate for mapping and analysis than Choropleth Map 1? (2-3 sentences)

Choropleth Map 2 is more appropriate for mapping and analysis than Choropleth Map 1 because the second one is per 1,000 people which means it is measuring of the frequency of cases per population unit. By doing this, the map visualized the data with the perspective of the size of the population and took into account discrepancies between the population of counties. Therefore, the data is more accurately visualized and more useful when making comparisons between counties.

Question 5. Describe the nature of the spatial pattern found in Choropleth Map 2. (1-2 sentences)

One pattern I noticed was that the rate of cases seems to be higher in counties that have a higher population which makes sense because contagious people have a higher chance of coming in contact with someone else and spreading the disease in more crowded urban areas.

Question 6. Explain the difference between Choropleth Map 3 and Choropleth Map 2. Which is easier for you to interpret? (2-3 sentences)

The difference between Choropleth Map 3 and Choropleth Map 2 is that the data is grouped in different ways, in the third map the last group covers a much larger range of rates from ~ 22 - 97 while the second map is from ~ 49 - 97. For me, the second map is easier to interpret because there is a more visible difference between the counties with higher rates, moderate rates and lower rates. To me, the third map makes the data look very dramatized and counties that have very different rates still appear to look very similar which I think is misleading (for example a county with a rate of ~22 cases and one with ~ 97 cases look very similar despite the incredibly large difference between the two numbers).
